. ### Migration Steps
The Accumulo AgeOff filter has been removed and replaced with store validation. The property accumulo.ageOffTimeInDays is no longer used. The schema validation functions you specify are now used to continually validate and remove invalid elements. This allows for custom expiration of elements as well as standard age off. 
If you were making use of the automatic Accumulo AgeOff filter then next time you create a new table it will no longer be added - instead a validator filter is added. 
Instead ensure each element group that you wish to be aged off has a timestamp property with a type similar to "timestamp", then in the types section add something similar to the following:
json
"timestamp": {
    "class": "java.lang.String",
    "validateFunctions":  [
      {
        "function": {
          "class": "gaffer.function.simple.filter.AgeOff",
          "ageOffDays": 365
        }
      }
    ]
}
To migrate to the new validator filter on an existing table do the following:
- Open the accumulo shell and remove the AgeOff iterator.
- Assemble a jar containing the main class AddUpdateTableIterator and any other functions or serialisers you are using in your schemas.
- Then run the AddUpdateTableIterator jar on accumulo with your new schema paths, property path and the 'update' argument.
. I'm going to close this as it is unlikely we will ever change the serialisation. Instead of trying to create a HyperLogLogPlus object in json you should consider writing the logic in Java and using an ElementGenerator or ObjectGenerator operation.. It is actually quite simple to allow new HyperLogLogPlus objects to be created from son, by adding optional 'p', 'sp' and 'offers' fields. For example you could create a new HyperLogLogPlus object by doing:
json
{
  "p": 30, 
  "sp": 30, 
  "offers": ["value1", "value2", "value3"]
}
This will be a simple change to the deserialisation logic. The way it is serialised into json will not change, these new fields will not be outputted into json so it will be backwards compatible.. ### Migration Steps
Schemas can now be written in 1 file - DataSchema and StoreSchema have been merged to form Schema. However, to reuse schema types and element groups across different stores it is recommended to split your schemas into small modules. 
Recommended modular schema approach
data schema
element groups and their corresponding types
json
{
  "entities": {
    "<entityGroupName>": {
      "vertex": "<vertexType>",
      "properties": {
        "<property name>": "<property type>"
      }
   }
 },
 "edges": {
   "<edgeGroupName>": {
      "source": "<sourceType>",
      "destination": "<destinationType>",
      "directed": "<directedType>",
      "properties": {
        "<property name>": "<property type>"
      }
    }
 }
}
data types
all types and their corresponding functions for validation
json
{
  "types": {
    "<type name>": {
      "class": "<class name>",
      "validateFunctions": [
        {
          "function": {
            "class": "<validate function class name>"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  }
}
store schema
store specific configuration such as the vertex serialiser
json
{
  "vertexSerialiserClass": "<serialiser class name>"
}
store types
all types and their corresponding functions for aggregation, additional store validation, store position, serialiser
json
{
  "types": {
    "simpleProperty": {
      "serialiserClass": "<serialiser class name>",
      "position": "<position e.g VALUE>",
      "aggregateFunction": {
        "class": "<aggregate function class name>"
      }
    }
  }
}
In some cases it would be useful to split the schemas out future, such as:
- the dataSchema could be split out into element groups to allow the groups to be shared across graphs
- the store types could be split out future to allow for stores that don't support aggregation.
