. Merged into develop-0.7.0. The functions library in Gaffer has been split into a separate project called koryphe. This has caused a large number of functions (filters, aggregators and transforms) to be moved and hence the package names have changed.
We have also aligned with Java 8 function interfaces:
FilterFunction -> Predicate
AggregateFunction -> BinaryOperator
TransformFunction -> Function
The interfaces for these methods has changed too.
FilterFunction.isValid -> Predicate.test
AggregateFunction.aggregate -> BinaryOperator.apply
SimpleAggregateFunction._aggregate -> KorypheBinaryOperator._apply
TransformFunction.transform -> Function.apply
The statelessClone and state methods have been removed.
this has also caused package names to be changed so match the java 8 packages.
```
uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.function.aggregate.FreqMapAggregator -> uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.binaryoperator.FreqMapAggregator
uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.function.aggregate.IntegerFreqMapAggregator -> uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.binaryoperator.IntegerFreqMapAggregator
uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.function.aggregate -> uk.gov.gchq.koryphe.impl.binaryoperator
uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.function.MapFilter -> uk.gov.koryphe.predicate.PredicateMap,
uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.function.filter -> uk.gov.gchq.koryphe.impl.predicate
uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.function.transform -> uk.gov.gchq.koryphe.impl.function
```
Implementations of FilterFunctions now need to extend KoryphePredicate. For FilterFunctions that require 2 or more inputs (X) you should implement KoryphePredicateX. The input annotation is no longer used.
Implementations of AggregateFunctions now need to implement KorypheBinaryOperator. The implementations should now be stateless. To merge 2 objects together, A and B, you can just add the contents of B to object A. The input/output annotations are no longer used.
Implementations of TransformFunctions now to implement KorypheFunction. For TransformFunctions that require 2 or more inputs (X) you should implement KorypheFunctionX. The input/output annotations are no longer used.
The ElementGenerator interface has been split into ElementGenerator and ObjectGenerator.
You will need to update your implementations to use the new interfaces.
The REST end point has been split into /graph/elementGenerators and /graph/objectGenerators
ElementGenerator.getElements -> ElementGenerator.apply
OneToOneElementGenerator.getElement -> OneToOneElementGenerator._apply
ElementGenerator.getObjects -> ObjectGenerator.apply
OneToOneElementGenerator.getObject -> OneToOneObjectGenerator._apply
