. These options do really increase the complexity of implementing a new Store. Perhaps we could remove some options or make some of them optional.. # Migration Steps
The following options have been removed:
- populateProperties (this never used to do anything)
- includeEntities (the view should be used to control if entities are required)
- includeEdges (the view should be used to control if edges are required)
- limitResults (users will now have to use the Limit operation)
- deduplicate (users will now have to use the ToSet operation)
A 'directedType' option has been added to replace includeEdges, this allows only directed or undirected edges to be filtered.
The hierarchy of some of the operations has also changed to try and avoid operations having illegal options. This change led to the removal of all Abstract Operation classes. All operation implementations now just need to implement Operation and any of the following interfaces they wish to make use of:
- Input
- Output
- InputOutput  (Use this instead of Input and Output if your operation takes both input and output.)
- MultiInput (Use this in addition if you operation takes multiple inputs. This will help with json serialisation)
- SeedMatching
- Validatable
- GraphFilters
- OperationView
- SeededGraphFilters
- Options
When writing a Operation Builder, you need to extend Operation.BaseBuilder and again implement the builders for the interfaces you selected above. See GetElements.Builder for an example.
A View can now only be set on Get operations. It doesn't make sense for a View to be supplied on operations such as AddElements and GenerateObjects.
Handlers for operations have now changed slightly due to Operation not haven't an output type. If you have an operation handler for an operation that implements Output. Then your handler should implement OutputOperationHandler instead of OperationHandler.. Merged into develop.
. Design idea:
In the schema, create a new array field called "indexedProperties". This would be populated as part of the store specific schema. Properties in a group that should be indexed should be added to this array. If configured to do aggregation, the indexed properties should be a subset of the groupBy property. This is due to the groupBy properties not being aggregated at ingest time so they remain constant. As they are constant they can be indexed easily.
In the accumulo store, a new table will be created for each different indexedProperty type. The new tables will be almost an exact copy of the main table, the difference will be that the rowId bytes will be swapped with the indexedProperty bytes. Aggregation and age off/validation should be the same as the main table. Doing this will have a significant performance and storage cost.
At query time a user should then be able to specify a property seed to query on. Depending on the property type accumulo will look the element up from the correct table.
