Graph hooks are now configured in json. This simplifies the configuration required to add graph hooks to a Gaffer rest api. You can now provide one json files containing the configuration for all of your graph hooks. For example:
json
[
  {
    "class": "uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.graph.hook.OperationChainLimiter",
    "opScores": {
      "uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.operation.Operation": 1,
      "uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.operation.impl.add.AddElements": 2,
      "uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.operation.impl.get.GetAllElement": 5,
      "uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.operation.impl.generate.GenerateObjects": 0
    },
    "authScores": {
        "User": 2,
        "SuperUser": 5
    }
  },
  {
    "class": "uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.graph.hook.AddOperationsToChain",
    "end": [
      {
        "class": "uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.operation.impl.Count"
      }
    ],
    "after": {
      "uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.operation.impl.get.GetAllElements": [
        {
          "class": "uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.operation.impl.Limit"
        }
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "class": "uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.graph.hook.OperationAuthoriser",
    "auths": {
      "uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.operation.Operation": [
        "User"
      ],
      "uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.operation.io.Output": [
        "ReadUser"
      ],
      "uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.operation.impl.add.AddElements": [
        "WriteUser"
      ],
      "uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.operation.impl.get.GetAdjacentIds": [
        "SuperUser"
      ],
      "uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.operation.impl.get.GetAllElements": [
        "AdminUser",
        "SuperUser"
      ]
    }
  }
]
Migration notes for individual Graph Hooks
OperationAuthoriser
Instead of supplying the opAuths.properties file, you now need to configure the hook in json using the auths field. auths is a map of operation class name to array of string authorisations. See above for a json example.
OperationChainLimiter (and ScoreOperationChainHandler)
Rather than providing the authScores.properties and opScores.properties files you now need to configure the hook in json using the authScores and opScores fields. See above for a json example.

authScores is a map of auth string to integer score.
opScores is a map of operation class name to integer score.

The ScoreOperationChainHandler score property files have also been removed and replaced with a single json file similar to OperationChainLimiter. The only difference with the json file is that it does not have a class name field.
For example:
ScoreOperationChainDeclaration.json:
```json
{
  "operations": [
    {
      "operation": "uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.operation.impl.ScoreOperationChain",
      "handler": {
        "class": "uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.store.operation.handler.ScoreOperationChainHandler",
        "opScores": {
          "uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.operation.Operation": 1,
          "uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.operation.impl.generate.GenerateObjects": 0
        },
        "authScores": {
          "TEST_USER": 4,
          "TEST_USER_ENHANCED": 10
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
```
REST API changes
The system properties have been removed:
- gaffer.operation.auths.path
- gaffer.graph.hook.add.operations.path
- gaffer.chain.limiter.enable
- gaffer.chain.limiter.operation.scores.path
- gaffer.chain.limiter.authorisation.scores.path
They have been replaced with a single property:
- gaffer.graph.hooks.path
this should be set to a path to your json file containing an array of graph hooks as shown above.. Merged into develop-0.8.0. Merged into develop.. # Migration Steps
JSONSerialiser is now a singleton and the methods on JSONSerialiser are now static. You will need to remove any instances you have of JSONSerialiser and instead just use the static methods on JSONSerialiser.
The behaviour of the JSONSerialiser ObjectMapper can be configured by extending the JSONSerialiser class and configuring the ObjectMapper. Child classes must has a default no argument constructor. You will then need to set the gaffer.serialiser.json.class property in your StoreProperties or as a System Property. You can also add modules to the ObjectMapper by writing an implementation of JSONSerialiserModules and registering it using the gaffer.serialiser.json.modules property in your StoreProperties or as a System Property.
If you use libraries like the Sketches library, then they may come with json serialisers that you can use. You can configure your store to use these serialisers by setting a property like:
properties
gaffer.serialiser.json.modules=uk.gov.gchq.gaffer.bitmap.serialisation.json.SketchesJsonModules
This property allows a csv of different modules to be configured.
Previously there were other ways of configuring the JSONSerialiser, such as in ExportToGafferResultCacheHandler and ProxyProperties. These have been removed in favour of configuring the JSONSerialiser once for the entire jvm.
