Previously, if you didn't manually set the timestamp value on an element these stores would set the value for you to the current time. This has caused several problems and therefore will no longer happen. If you want to the current time or a different value you will need to set it yourself.
In Accumulo the default timestamp value will now be 1. 
In HBase the default timestamp value will now be a random value based on the current time and a random number.
Setting the timestampProperty field in a schema for these stores is now deemed an advanced feature and should only be used if you really understand the effects. We recommend you don't use the timestampProperty in the schema.. Fixed as part of #1565.. Merged into develop.. Just been looking into moving it into a store property. It does cause the Accumulo key packages to become a bit untidy. They now need to know about the schema and this new timestamp property. Also,  any classes that serialise/deserialise the key packages also need to know about this new property.
I think the timestamp property should still be part of the schema, as it is applicable to a given schema. If we put it in the store properties then those properties are tied to the schema and they should be independent.
